### Phase 1 - Create the standalone repository safely

- ŌśÉ Create the DwarfSpec repository separately from the active DwarfUI
  workspace.
- ŌśÉ Preserve relevant file history with a filtered clone or subtree extraction
  performed against a disposable clone; do not rewrite DwarfUI history.
- ŌśÉ Add the target directory layout, README, license, changelog, and repository
  development instructions.
- ŌśÉ Establish Lua 5.3-compatible formatting and syntax checks.
- ŌśÉ Establish a local Busted unit-test command for DwarfSpec's own code.
- ŌśÉ Move generic framework modules and tests without changing behavior.
- ŌśÉ Keep the first extraction commit mechanically reviewable and separate from
  later renaming and packaging changes where practical.
- ŌśÉ Confirm no DwarfUI product modules or tooltip-specific fixtures were copied
  into DwarfSpec.

Exit: DwarfSpec has an independent build and unit-test baseline containing
only reusable framework code.

### Phase 2 - Rename the public API from `dy` to `ds`

- ŌśÉ Rename the driver module, local symbols, parameters, lifecycle installer,
  specs, and documentation from `dy` to `ds`.
- ŌśÉ Export `ds` through Busted's isolated environment.
- ŌśÉ Prove `rawget(_G, 'ds')` and `rawget(_G, 'dy')` are both `nil` during a
  running live spec.
- ŌśÉ Install automatic root `before_each` and `after_each` hooks through
  `ds.reset()`.
- ŌśÉ Update operational errors such as invalid waits and cleanup failures to use
  `ds` terminology.
- ŌśÉ Update every moved generic spec to call `ds.*`.
- ŌśÉ Update every retained DwarfUI live spec to call `ds.*`.
- ŌśÉ Remove the old `dy` export and module completely; do not retain an alias.
- ŌśÉ Add regression coverage that fails if `dy` becomes available again.
- ŌśÉ Run a complete text and filename audit for the old public name.

Exit: the framework and DwarfUI consumer tests expose only `ds.*`, with no
process-global export or compatibility alias.

### Phase 3 - Generalize package and consumer boundaries

- ŌśÉ Replace DwarfUI-relative bootstrap, support, spec, fixture, overlay, and
  result paths with resolved DwarfSpec package and consumer-project inputs.
- ŌśÉ Discover the project root from an explicit CLI option or current working
  directory without assuming a DwarfUI layout.
- ŌśÉ Discover live specs only through `Tests/**/*_spec.ds.lua`, including nested
  directories, with deterministic ordering and no overlap with ordinary Busted
  unit specs.
- ŌśÉ Load optional global configuration and custom command modules from
  `Tests/dwarfspec/*.lua` with deterministic order, schema validation,
  duplicate-command rejection, and actionable errors.
- ŌśÉ Define the custom command registration contract and make registered
  commands available through the isolated `ds` object without writing to `_G`.
- ŌśÉ Generalize fixture loading so specs and custom commands can explicitly
  import fixtures from any supported import location without a library-owned
  product allowlist or mandatory fixture root.
- ŌśÉ Document `Tests/**/fixtures/*.fixture.lua` as the recommended convention
  and prove fixtures outside that convention remain usable when importable.
- ŌśÉ Generalize overlay fixture staging from explicitly imported fixture
  definitions while retaining safe target validation, unique names, rescans,
  and guaranteed removal.
- ŌśÉ Provide an explicit extension seam for consumer diagnostic adapters so
  DwarfUI can expose tooltip diagnostics without adding product knowledge to
  DwarfSpec.
- ŌśÉ Move active-run ownership to `dfhack.dwarfspec` and reject incompatible or
  overlapping hosts clearly.
- ŌśÉ Rename status reports, result paths, temporary files, and diagnostic labels
  to DwarfSpec branding.
- ŌśÉ Preserve generation checks, lease recovery, idempotent LIFO cleanup, and
  stale-callback rejection.

Exit: DwarfSpec can run a minimal fixture project that contains no DwarfUI
paths, modules, or branding.

### Phase 4 - Replace the PowerShell runner with the DwarfSpec command

- ŌśÉ Implement a Lua CLI entry point installed as `dwarfspec`.
- ŌśÉ Implement subcommand dispatch; bare `dwarfspec` must display help and must
  not discover, connect, or run tests implicitly.
- ŌśÉ Implement `dwarfspec list` and `dwarfspec list <glob>` with deterministic
  output and no test-body or hook execution.
- ŌśÉ Implement `dwarfspec run` to execute all discovered tests.
- ŌśÉ Implement `dwarfspec run <glob>` using exactly the identities and matcher
  exposed by `list`.
- ŌśÉ Freeze and document canonical test identities, glob syntax, escaping,
  case-sensitivity, multiple-match behavior, and no-match behavior.
- ŌśÉ Support command help, version output, project-root selection, Busted
  filters, timeouts, overlay fixtures, result-directory selection, and an
  explicit abort path.
- ŌśÉ Resolve `dfhack-run` through `DFHACK_RUNNER`, `DFHACK_ROOT`, or `PATH` and
  print the resolved executable in verbose diagnostics.
- ŌśÉ Verify DFHack connectivity before starting a run and report a concise
  actionable error when DFHack is not running.
- ŌśÉ Locate DwarfSpec's installed bootstrap modules without copying them into
  the consumer repository or permanent DFHack script directories.
- ŌśÉ Start the in-process host, poll native JSON status reports, stream Busted
  progress, enforce the wall-clock timeout, and preserve final diagnostics.
- ŌśÉ Return zero only for a passing Busted result with confirmed cleanup.
- ŌśÉ Return nonzero for dependency, connection, discovery, host, Busted,
  timeout, abort, malformed-report, and cleanup failures.
- ŌśÉ Preserve safe overlay staging and final rescans without requiring
  PowerShell.
- ŌśÉ Test subcommand parsing, list/run parity, glob matching, malformed and
  unmatched globs, quoting, paths with spaces, exit-code propagation,
  interruption, and cleanup on Windows and at least one Unix-like environment.
- ŌśÉ Keep `Run-AutomationTests.ps1` available only as a temporary parity oracle
  until the installed command passes all equivalent cases.

Exit: a developer can inspect the suite with `dwarfspec list`, select it with
the same globs, and run it with `dwarfspec run`, receiving the same or better
diagnostics and exit behavior as the old runner.

### Phase 5 - Package DwarfSpec with LuaRocks

- ŌśÉ Add a rockspec using rockspec format 3.0 and an initial version such as
  `0.1.0-1`.
- ŌśÉ Declare the supported Lua versions and DwarfSpec's runtime dependency on
  the compatible Busted release.
- ŌśÉ Install all public/internal Lua modules under the `dwarfspec.*` namespace.
- ŌśÉ Install the `dwarfspec` command with `build.install.bin`.
- ŌśÉ Keep the rock platform-independent and verify it builds as an `.all.rock`.
- ŌśÉ Ensure modules loaded inside DFHack are pure Lua and never resolve external
  Lua 5.4 native libraries in the Lua 5.3 process.
- ŌśÉ Run `luarocks lint` and build both source and binary rocks.
- ŌśÉ Install the built rock into an empty temporary rock tree.
- ŌśÉ Prove `require('dwarfspec.ds')`, CLI help, configuration discovery, and
  Busted dependency resolution from the clean tree.
- ŌśÉ Prove an installation made through an external Lua 5.4 toolchain can still
  launch the Lua 5.3-compatible in-process DFHack host through its pure-Lua
  paths and adapters.
- ŌśÉ Document installation from a local rock, development rock server, and the
  public LuaRocks server.
- ŌśÉ Add a release checklist covering version revision, changelog, pack, clean
  install, live proof, tag, upload, and post-upload install verification.

Exit: a clean machine with LuaRocks can install DwarfSpec and receive both the
library modules and working `dwarfspec` command.

### Phase 6 - Convert DwarfUI into the first external consumer

- ŌśÉ Add a DwarfUI rockspec or update its existing dependency metadata to
  declare `dwarfspec ~> 0.1` as a `test_dependency`.
- ŌśÉ Rename and move retained DwarfUI live specs beneath `Tests/` with the
  `*_spec.ds.lua` suffix.
- ŌśÉ Move retained DwarfUI fixtures to importable locations, preferably beside
  their feature specs under `Tests/**/fixtures/*.fixture.lua`.
- ŌśÉ Put any DwarfUI-wide DwarfSpec configuration and tooltip-specific custom
  commands under `Tests/dwarfspec/*.lua`.
- ŌśÉ Register the DwarfUI tooltip diagnostic adapter through DwarfSpec's
  consumer extension seam.
- ŌśÉ Run every DwarfUI live spec through the locally installed DwarfSpec rock,
  not through source files reachable from the sibling DwarfSpec checkout.
- ŌśÉ Prove screen fixtures, overlay fixtures, pointer input, render waits,
  tooltip diagnostics, failure reporting, and automatic setup/teardown.
- ŌśÉ Prove the DwarfSpec package can be absent from DwarfUI's production package
  payload and is needed only by developers/tests.
- ŌśÉ Remove generic framework modules, tests, fixtures, and copied dependencies
  from DwarfUI after parity is established.
- ŌśÉ Delete `Tools/Run-AutomationTests.ps1` after the installed command passes
  the full DwarfUI suite plus deliberate failure, timeout, abort, and cleanup
  cases.
- ŌśÉ Update DwarfUI documentation to describe it as a DwarfSpec consumer and
  link to DwarfSpec for framework documentation.
- ŌśÉ Verify the DwarfUI production package contains no DwarfSpec framework or
  automation-test files.

Exit: DwarfUI consumes DwarfSpec exactly as an unrelated project would and no
longer owns a private copy or private runner.

### Phase 7 - Validate installation and release readiness

- ŌśÉ From a clean temporary project, declare DwarfSpec only through
  `test_dependencies`, run `luarocks test --prepare`, write
  `Tests/smoke_spec.ds.lua`, list it with `dwarfspec list`, and run it with
  `dwarfspec run`.
- ŌśÉ In the clean project, prove `Tests/dwarfspec/config.lua` applies global
  configuration and another `Tests/dwarfspec/*.lua` module registers a custom
  `ds` command.
- ŌśÉ Prove a co-located `Tests/smoke/fixtures/example.fixture.lua` fixture and a
  fixture from another supported import location can both be used explicitly.
- ŌśÉ In a second clean project, configure `test.command = 'dwarfspec'` with
  `test.flags = { 'run' }` and prove `luarocks test` installs dependencies and
  executes the live suite.
- ŌśÉ Prove a project with an existing local Busted `test` entry can keep it and
  run `dwarfspec list` and `dwarfspec run` independently.
- ŌśÉ Prove `list <glob>` and `run <glob>` select identical canonical test
  identities for exact, wildcard, nested-path, and no-match cases.
- ŌśÉ Verify deterministic discovery and filtering across nested spec paths.
- ŌśÉ Verify pass, assertion failure, operational error, pending, malformed spec,
  filter-no-match, timeout, explicit abort, lost runner, and cleanup failure.
- ŌśÉ Verify no run leaves screens, pointer patches, timers, overlays, staged
  scripts, run ownership, or Busted globals behind.
- ŌśÉ Verify the physical mouse need not be over the game window.
- ŌśÉ Verify package uninstall removes DwarfSpec's modules and command without
  touching consumer specs, fixtures, reports, DFHack, or game data.
- ŌśÉ Publish the initial release only after the clean-project and DwarfUI
  installed-package proofs pass.
- ŌśÉ Tag the proven source commit and record the published rock checksum and
  DwarfUI consumer revision.

Exit: the published package supports the promised install-write-run workflow
and DwarfUI passes against the same artifact available to other projects.

## Verification matrix

| Layer | Required proof |
|---|---|
| DwarfSpec syntax | All shipped and test Lua parses under Lua 5.3; external tooling also passes under Lua 5.4. |
| DwarfSpec unit | `Tests/**/*_spec.ds.lua` discovery, canonical identities, list/run glob parity, filters, configuration, custom commands, fixture imports, paths, scheduler, cleanup, reporting, adapters, CLI parsing, and exit codes pass outside DFHack. |
| Rock metadata | Rockspec lint, source rock build, `.all.rock` build, clean-tree install, module load, and command installation pass. |
| Generic live | In-process Busted host, `ds` isolation, frame yields, pointer/input operations, cleanup, failure, timeout, abort, and lease recovery pass in DFHack. |
| DwarfUI local | Existing DwarfUI unit, syntax, build, and package checks pass independently of live automation. |
| DwarfUI live | Tooltip screen and overlay specs pass through the installed DwarfSpec rock with confirmed cleanup. |
| Consumer smoke | A clean example project installs DwarfSpec only as a declared test dependency and runs without a repository-specific runner. |
| Release artifact | A fresh install of the uploaded rock reproduces CLI, generic live, and DwarfUI consumer results. |

## Basic acceptance criteria

- ŌśÉ DwarfSpec exists in its own repository with reusable framework code and no
  DwarfUI product knowledge.
- ŌśÉ The public automation surface is exclusively `ds.*`.
- ŌśÉ `ds` is available inside isolated Busted spec environments and absent from
  process-wide globals.
- ŌśÉ Busted remains the sole test structure, hook, assertion, and result system.
- ŌśÉ The package installs through LuaRocks as a pure-Lua library and installs a
  working `dwarfspec` command.
- ŌśÉ Bare `dwarfspec` displays help and never implicitly runs tests.
- ŌśÉ `dwarfspec list` lists all canonical test identities without executing
  tests or hooks.
- ŌśÉ `dwarfspec run` runs all discovered tests.
- ŌśÉ `dwarfspec list <glob>` and `dwarfspec run <glob>` select the same tests.
- ŌśÉ Consumers can declare DwarfSpec through `test_dependencies`.
- ŌśÉ The default install-write-run workflow requires no consumer-specific
  PowerShell, shell, batch, or Lua runner script.
- ŌśÉ DwarfSpec resolves and invokes the supported `dfhack-run` bridge without
  exposing transport details to test authors.
- ŌśÉ Consumer specs are discovered only as `Tests/**/*_spec.ds.lua`.
- ŌśÉ Global configuration and custom commands load only from
  `Tests/dwarfspec/*.lua`.
- ŌśÉ Fixtures can be imported from any supported import location, with
  `Tests/**/fixtures/*.fixture.lua` documented as the recommended convention.
- ŌśÉ Product-specific diagnostics are supplied through an extension seam and
  do not leak into the DwarfSpec package.
- ŌśÉ DwarfUI passes all retained live specs against an installed DwarfSpec rock.
- ŌśÉ Failure, timeout, abort, and lost-runner paths all produce nonzero status
  and confirmed cleanup.
- ŌśÉ The DwarfUI production package does not contain DwarfSpec or live-test
  development files.
- ŌśÉ The old `dy` API, DwarfUI automation namespace, JSON prefix, private host
  copy, and PowerShell runner are removed after parity.
- ŌśÉ The published rock can be installed and exercised from a clean project.

## Stop-and-discuss blockers

Stop before broadening or changing the architecture if any of the following is
encountered:

- the new repository destination, ownership, license, or publication target is
  unavailable or ambiguous;
- LuaRocks cannot install a reliable `dwarfspec` command on a supported host
  without requiring a consumer-owned wrapper;
- the installed rock cannot expose its pure-Lua Busted dependencies safely to
  DFHack's Lua 5.3 context;
- launching an installed bootstrap requires permanently copying DwarfSpec into
  DFHack or the consumer repository;
- explicit fixture imports cannot preserve the current loading-safety and
  cleanup contracts;
- the cross-platform Lua CLI cannot reproduce timeout, interruption, JSON
  reporting, overlay staging, or exit-code behavior of the current runner; or
- DwarfUI only passes while importing files directly from a sibling DwarfSpec
  checkout instead of the installed rock.

## Deferred capabilities

- Launching, restarting, or automatically updating Dwarf Fortress or DFHack.
- Automatically loading or restoring a save.
- Parallel live suites or multiple simultaneous runs in one DFHack process.
- Persistent-world mutation tests.
- Pixel screenshots and golden-image comparison.
- CSS-like selectors beyond the live DFHack object and `view_id` contracts.
- A `dy` compatibility package or migration shim.
